The Geometric Probability Distribution & Weak Law of Large Numbers

Let us roll a KK sided die with numbers 11, . . . , KK written on them where K>1K>1. Each number is equally likely to be rolled. Let XX be a random variable representing the number of rolls needed to get the number KK for the first time. (Note: number of rolls includes the roll where KK appears.)

  1. On any roll, what is the probability of rolling the value KK?
# 1/k

  1. What are all of the possible values of XX? 1<=xx<+∞

  2. Create a function with arguments, K and n_sims, with n_sims representing the number of times we should play out this scenario. Your function should return the number of times the die was rolled in order to get the value K. (Helpful hint: Try using a while loop)

# Through function we can get how many times we need to get k
nfact <- function(k){
  x<-0
  t<-0
  while(x!=k)
  {
  x<-sample(x = 1:k, size = 1, replace = FALSE)
  t<-t+1
  }
  return(t)
}
# Then through nfact2 we can get how many times we need to get the value k 
nfact2 <- function(k,n_sims){
  
  nfact <- function(k){
  x<-0
  t<-0
  while(x!=k)
  {
  x<-sample(x = 1:k, size = 1, replace = FALSE)
  t<-t+1
  }
  return(t)
  
}
  q<-replicate(n_sims,nfact(k))
  return(q)
}

The Exponential Probability Distribution & Central Limit Theorem

The magnitude of earthquakes in North America can be modeled as having an exponential distribution with mean μμ of 2.4.

For an exponential distribution:

Mean: E[X]=λE[X]=λ

Variance: E[X2]−(E[X])2=λ2E[X2]−(E[X])2=λ2

  1. Simulate 1000 earthquakes and plot the distribution of Richter Scale values (Hint: rexp(x, rate = 1/lambda)). Let this data represent XX. Create a histogram of XX and describe the shape of this distribution. How does this differ from the normal distribution?

  1. Create a function which will simulate multiple samples drawn from an exponential distribution with λλ = 2.4 (Hint: rexp(x, rate = 1/lambda) and return a vector containing the mean values for each of your samples. Your arguments should be lamba, n_sims for the number of simulations per sample, and n_samples for the number of samples of size n_sims to be created.
funk21<-function(lambda,n_sim,n_samples){
  k=0
  mea<-c()
  while(k!=n_samples)
  {
    k=k+1
    y<-mean(rexp(n_sim,1/lambda))
    mea<-c(mea,y)
  }
  return(mea)
}
